The comparison of Figure~\ref{fig:maps_fx} (FX-runs) and Figure~\ref{fig:maps_sc} (SC-ULTRA-MW-L8) highlights the sensitivity of the corona dynamics to the SN seeding scheme, 
i.e. on the location of the SNe. In the FX case, SNe explode with uniform probability in a horizontal slab of fixed thickness (Table~\ref{tab:parameters2}). The 
probability that a SN explodes in a low density region is relatively high. Since SNe that explode in low density regions are more efficient at heating the gas, 
the FX runs typically have a much hotter and more dynamic atmosphere. In the SC runs, by contrast, SNe preferentially explode in higher density regions close to the mid-plane; as a result,  SNe
heating is less efficient in the SC case and the atmosphere is colder than in the FX case.   This translates into a much weaker outflow (\S \ref{sec:energetics}).   

